<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence from the Greater London Authority  (CYS 060)</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence from the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> Greater London Authority  (CYS 060)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Thank you for inviting us to submit evidence on cycling safety. We hope that your inquiry can help im</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">prove the quality of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">debate on this issue. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">1. Is cycling safe?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:10.78pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Yes. The recent terrible series of deaths on London’s roads has rightly captured public and political attention. The Mayor is deeply saddened and concerned by it. But death and serious injury have always been </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">very </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rare</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, and have become </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rarer in recent year</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s. Spates of this nature are even more unusual. We believe there are serious dangers, which we describe in section 2 below, in taking the exceptional as representative of the general. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:10.78pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">More broadly, cycling is far more likely to prolong your life than to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">end it; and far more likely to improve your health than to harm it. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">rate of cyclist fatalities has</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> fallen dramatically in recent years. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:10.78pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Over the last ten years, cyclist fatalities per journey for London cycling have fallen by more than half. In </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2002, there were 118 million cycle journeys</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in London, of which 20 (one in every 5.9 million) ended in death. In 2011, there were 209 million cycle journeys of which 16 ended in death, one in around every 13 million. 2012 figures for the numbers of journe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ys are not final, but are likely to be around the same as 2011. There were 14 deaths in 2012, giving a rate of around one death in every 15 million journeys. Th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ere have</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> been 14 deaths so far in 2013, with just over a month to go.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Serious injury rat</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">es have</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> also fallen</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:10.78pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In 2002, London’s 118 million cycle journeys resulted in 394 serious injuries. One journey in every 299,000 ended in serious injury. 2012 figures for the numbers of journeys are not final, but are likely to be around 209 million. There were</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> 657 serious injuries in 2012, a rate of one in every 320,000 journeys.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Although it is possible to draw some conclusions from deaths over the medium term, it is much harder to draw any conclusions from relatively short-term events. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:10.78pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In November 2013, for</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> instance, there were as many deaths in 13 days as there were in the first eight months of the year. In the six months to June, three cyclists died in London, one every two months. In the recent spate, it was </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">six in two weeks</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. It seems unlikely that the sa</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">me roads were thirty times more dangerous</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in November than in January or</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> February. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:10.78pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It is, we believe, possible to draw some conclusions from deaths over, for instance, a t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">en</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">-year period because a greater number of events </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">are</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> involved.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Annual cyclist </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">fatalities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> do appear to have reduced from a range roughly in the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">low twenties and high teens in the 1990s and 2000s to a range in the mid-teens in the 2010s. But it is not possible to draw conclusions from shorter-term events. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">London’s cycle casualty rat</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">es are comparable to, or better than, most equivalent foreign cities, though exact comparisons are difficult. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:10.78pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In 2012</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> there were five cyclist fatalities </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in the city of Paris (an area only slightly larger than London’s zone 1), compared with one death in London’s zone 1. In the wider area of greater Paris, Ile-de-France, there were 17 deaths.  Ile-de-France has about </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">40</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> per cent more people than greater Lon</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">don, so the equivalent per head is roughly the same. In New York </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">City </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">there were </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">20</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> deaths. Cyclist fatalities per journey</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in these cities as a proportion of all journeys </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> similar to or lower than those in London. In Berlin, where cycling has a higher mo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">d</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> share, there were 15 deaths. Serious injury figures are harder to compare because of differing definitions of what constitutes a serious injury.  </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">The concept of “subjective safety” is sometimes employed to argue against these empirical truths. We acce</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">pt the importance of this.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:10.78pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">“Subjective safety” is broadly the idea that even though the figures say cycling is safe, people do not beli</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">eve it to be so. This is partly, of course, a self-fulfilling prophecy. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Cycling advocates and the media draw unwarrant</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ed conclusions from individual events, then cite in their support a phenomenon caused in part by their own conclusions.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:10.78pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">But it is also partly real. Although cycling may objectively </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">safe, it is hard to dispute that cycling on many of our busy roads doe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s not </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">feel </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">su</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">fficiently safe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. Fears about safety are cited by many people as the key barrier to their taking up cycling. So creating a greater feeling of safety on the roads is one of the core purposes of the Mayor’s </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">recent </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">£9</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">13</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> million </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Cycling V</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ision </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">inve</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">stment programme </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">– for a discussion of this, and of subjectivity in the debate, see section 2 below. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Some objective and empirical signs are also causing us growing concern.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:10.78pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The rate of serious cycling injuries per journey in London remains historically </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">very low</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> (it is, for instance, half what it was in the 1990s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> However, it has recently started to rise, though the increase is small and the rate remains below the levels of ten years ago. It is too early to say whether a few years’ figures represent a tr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">end, but we a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">re increasingly concerned by it. This </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">was a key factor spurring the Mayor to launch his recent and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">highly ambitious Cycling Vision investment programme (see section 2 below.) </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Cycling is far more likely to prolong your life than to end it; an</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">d more likely to improve your health than to harm it.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:10.78pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Regular cyclists have, on average, the fitness of someone at least 10 years younger. They </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">are half</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> as likely than average to suffer from heart disease, 27 per cent less likely to have a stroke, and w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ill live, on average, more</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> than two years longer. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">A British Medical Association (BMA) report studied the risk of injuries to cyclists against the benefits to the individual’s health from regular cycling. The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">culmination of the report was that the evidence </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">favours the promotion of cycling by a factor of around twenty to one. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Cycling will even prolong other people’s lives. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:10.78pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In June 2012, a report for the Central London Air Quality Cluster group of local authorities found that if just 14 per cent of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">journeys in central Lo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ndon were cycled – an </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">achievable target - emissions there of the greatest vehicle pollutant, NOx, would fall by 30 per cent, or 453 tonnes a year. Emissions of the other main pollutant, particularate matter, would fall by 24 per cent,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> or 33.8 tonnes a year. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:10.78pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Poor air quality affects all those who live, work and visit London.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> The Greater London Authority (GLA) estimated that poor air quality contributed to over 4,000 premature deaths in London in 2008.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:10.78pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Increased bicycle use could therefore, over the years ahead, save literally hundreds, even thousands, of people’s lives, even if they never cycle and have no intention of cycling. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">What can central and local government do to improve cycle safety? </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:10.78pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Cycli</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ng is safe, but w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e are clear that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">it</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">could and should be safer. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">London </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">has </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the country’s most substantial plans to ensure that it will be safer. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:10.78pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Earlier this year, in his “Cycling Vision,” the Mayor announced that he would invest £913 million in cycling </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">over the next ten years – more than two and a half times London’s  previous spend, and more than three times what the Government is investing for the whole of the rest of the country put together. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:10.78pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">A “cycling commissioner,” Andrew Gilligan, has been appoi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nted to deliver the Vision, making cycling the only transport mode with its own representative on the Mayor’s senior staff. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:10.78pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Vision was described even by the Mayor’s habitual critics, such as The Guardian newspaper, as “truly bold” and as offering “th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e possibility of re-shaping the way Londoners transport themselves over the coming decades.” It has cross-party support. The Vision is aimed not just at existing cyclists, but at people who would like to cycle, but feel unable to, often because they are af</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">raid. Addressing danger and perceptions of danger is even more important for this group. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:10.78pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The capital has a very large number of cyclists; 24 per cent of all vehicles on the roads of central London in the morning rush hour are now bicycles. The Vision was</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> borne of the need to cater for them. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:10.78pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">However, we are also concerned that the nature of the debate on cycling safety paradoxically risks making our improvements, and true progress on safety, harder to achieve. We suggest that those outside government, as</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> well as within it, also have responsibilities. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Safety improvement is a partnership with many partners. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:10.78pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It is often assumed that the Mayor controls all London’s roads. In fact, he controls only 5 per cent of them, the so-called Transport for London Road Network. These are the busiest roads, carrying 30 per cent of the traffic. The rest are owned largely by t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">he 33 London boroughs and the Mayor must proceed by agreement with them on most matters regarding cycling. Casualties on the TfL and borough roads are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">similar</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in proportion to the amount of traffic they carry. A co-ordinated approach to cycling infrastruct</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ure and enforcement is essential between TfL and the boroughs and is one of the key responsibilities of the Cycling Commissioner. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:10.78pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">There is also close liaison with the police, who are part of the GLA “family,” on enforcement matters (see below.)</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">We take </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">a smart, targeted approach to safety. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:10.78pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We have a long history of detailed research on the causality of serious and fatal cycle collisions and this drove the 2010 Cycle Safety Action Plan, and new research is underpinning the updating of this plan</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">That is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> why we have been able to reduce it. Most serious </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">casualties </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">fatalities </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">happen in two ways: while travelling through the busiest junctions, or in contact with heavy lorries, particularly construction lorries, or both. Around 85 per cent of cyclist inju</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ries in London occur at or close to junctions.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:10.78pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">TfL has</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> designed a template “cycle-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">separated</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> junction” which we intend to install along the Superhighway routes (see below) and at a number of other busy junctions not on the routes. The junctions include seg</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">regated approaches for cyclists and cycle-specific traffic lights, with a separate traffic phase for cyclists, to minimise conflict between them and motor vehicles. We </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">h</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ve also done off-street trials of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a number of other innovations, such as Dutch-style c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ycle-separated roundabouts, which we will test on the road network next year. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:10.78pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">TfL has</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> a major programme to completely remodel the 33 worst junctions and gyratories in London, including Elephant &amp; Castle, Aldgate, Vauxhall, Tower, Swiss Cottage and Blackf</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">riars. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:10.78pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">See section 3 below for how we are tackling the issues raised by heavy lorries. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">We believe route improvements, including segregation, are essential to improve safety – but more so perceived safety. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:10.78pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Only around 15</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> cent of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">cycle </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">collisio</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ns</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> h</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">appe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">n on links – that is, the sections of route between junctions. The need here is to improve the perception of safety</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s well as to improve their actual safety</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We will create two clear kinds of branded route. The first will be a number of new high-capacity Superhighways, mostly on main roads, for fast commuters. Most of these will run fully physically segregated from the rest of the traffic, or “semi-segregated” </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">(using traffic wands or “light segregation”) where roadspace does not allow full segregation. Other portions will be on low-traffic streets. There will be few, if any, unprotected sections on busy roads. The four existing Superhighways will also be upgrade</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">d to the same standards. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:10.78pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The new routes include the longest substantially-segregated urban cycle route in Europe, running for around 20 miles east-west through the heart of Central London and along the Westway flyover, where a traffic lane will be remove</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">d. The Westway, symbol of how the car tore up our cities, will now become a symbol of how they are being claimed for the bike. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:10.78pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The other main kind of route is the “Quietways,” a cross-London network of high-quality guided routes created on back streets, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">through parks and along canal towpaths for those who prefer to avoid the main roads. They will be direct; they will be clearly signed, making them easy to follow; and they will not give up at the difficult places. We believe that these routes will be parti</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">cu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">larly attractive to the new and less confident </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">cyclists we want to attract. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:10.78pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Segregation is not the only solution. Other forms of intervention, such as “filtered permeability,” have been used to great effect – for instance, in the London Borough of Hackney, where the number of cycling trips is the highest in London. There is very l</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ittle segregation in Hackney. Permeability means not completely separating bikes and cars, but making the existing streets join up better for cyclists (and pedestrians) than they do for cars, by for instance blocking rat-run type streets to traffic. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:10.78pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Beca</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">use they are on low-traffic streets </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">with little or</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> no HGV traffic, Quietways will mostly be unsegregated, though</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> segregation will be provided where</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> they need to cross a difficult main road junction or need to briefly join a main road for the sake of direct</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ness. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">TfL and the boroughs</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> support and provide better training and advice for drivers and cyclists. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:10.78pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We fund free cycle training for every schoolchild in London who wants it, and for adults. We are currently running a major “safety tips” advertising and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> marketing campaign which is now being copied nationally. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Metropolitan Police</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">, City of London Police and TfL </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">are</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> increasing enforcement </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">against bad driving and cycling</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:10.78pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Transport for London funds the Safer Transport Command, a unit of the Metropolit</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">an Police, and the Cycle Task Force, a bicycle unit within this. Under the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Cycling </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Vision the CTF has been increased in size by 28% and one of their principal jobs is to carry out cycle-focused enforcement (both against behaviour which endangers cyclists a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nd dangerous behaviour by cyclists.) </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:10.78pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The recent spate of deaths has prompted one of the largest police operations of its kind ever undertaken in London, with officers at 166 main road junctions stopping motorists and cyclists, offering safety advice and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ticketing those found to be driving unsafely. Around 150 tickets were issued on the first day alone. A total of 2,500 officers will be involved in the operation. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:10.78pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">For lorry enforcement, see below.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">We are promoting safety in a number of other ways. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:10.78pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">are funding “cycle to school partnerships,” where communities </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">design their own safe cycling routes to school, including segregated infrastructure, new and better crossings and filtered permeability. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The first pilot schemes will begin next year. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We have ins</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">talled a number of 20mph speed limits on TfL’s road network and are considering further locations for them. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Change takes time – and the roads are not just for cyclists. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:10.78pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal">Tragedies can lead to bad decisions: the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> impulse is to do something, anything, even if it is the wrong thing. But the Mayor has promised that this programme will be done properly. Most of the Superhighway routes and junctions are extremely complicated and serve many different users. It is essent</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ial that we not make overnight panic changes that might make cyclists safer at the expense of other people’s safety. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:10.78pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">There were 69 pedestrians killed on London’s roads in 2012, a number which seems to be of far less interest than the much smaller number </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of cyclist deaths. Pedestrians</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> may</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> lack cyclists’ political clout - but they are just as important to us, these are their roads as well, and everything we do has to work for them too. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:10.78pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Buses and their passengers are also a major issue for us. Most main ro</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ads in London are also </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">busy </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">bus routes. If the segregated cycle </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">lane</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> goes between the bus and the pavement, everyone getting off a bus would step straight into the lane, risking being hit by a cyclist. There are solutions to this problem, but </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">not everywher</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:10.78pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Changes also need to be agreed with the 33 boroughs and with others affected, such as residents, local businesses, the bus operators and other infrastructure owners.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:10.78pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">That is why this cannot be done overnight. But the first routes and junctions will</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">start to appear next year. O</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ur complete </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">S</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">uperhighway network, the great majority of our </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">new major </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">junctions and the majority of our quietway routes will be in place by 2016.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">The Government and EU need to act too.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:10.78pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Some of the actions </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">urged on us are outsi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">de our legal power</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Currently, EU or Whiteh</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">all regulations prevent us </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">from doing a number of important things for cycle safety. We have been strongly lobbying both the Government</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and the EU for changes to their</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> often highly prescriptive rules. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In June the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Mayor wrote to the Transport S</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ecretary with a list of requested changes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. We understand that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a reply will be given shortly. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Our key </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">“asks”</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> from Whitehall include: </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 30.2pt; padding-left:5.8pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">bigger advanced stop lanes (bike boxes) at traffic lights; </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 30.2pt; padding-left:5.8pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">low-level traffic light sign</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">al repeaters at a height cyclists can see them; </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 30.2pt; padding-left:5.8pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">less prescriptive rules on junctions, to allow greater cycle safety phases; </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 30.2pt; padding-left:5.8pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">less prescriptive rules on signage, allowing easier wayfinding for “quietway” cycle routes; </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 30.2pt; padding-left:5.8pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">removal of exemptions from safety restrictions for certain kinds of heavy lorry; </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 30.2pt; padding-left:5.8pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the ability to enforce against encroachment into advanced stop lanes ourselves; and </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 30.2pt; padding-left:5.8pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the ability to enforce against vehicle encroachment into mandatory cycle lanes ourselve</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:10.78pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Currently, only the police can enforce against cycle lane and ASL enroachment, and they understandably have many other calls on their time. If TfL were allowed to do it (as it is already allowed to with bus lanes) enforcement could be stepped up. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:10.78pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Mayor has also written to the Minister of Justice calling for tougher sentences against motorists and lorry drivers who hurt or kill cyclists. At the moment, many sentences are insufficient. The Mayor’s Sentencing Unit is monitoring sentencing for these c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rimes and intends to make this a priority in 2014. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:10.78pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Our key wishes from the EU are for changes to directives</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">96/53/EC </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2007/38/EC </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">which specify what a lorry’s cab should look like</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and the mirrors it is fitted with</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. We want this in order that a safer lo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rry, with fewer blind-spots for the driver, can be designed. Regrettably, this life-saving change appears to be bogged down in Brussels at the moment. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">November 2013</span><br style="page-break-before:always; clear:both" /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">There is a need to raise the quality of the debate. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:10.78pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The recent spate of cyclist deaths (and the deat</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">hs last year) has repeatedly been described as “carnage.” Comparisons have been made to the danger faced by British soldiers in Afghanistan.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:10.78pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Fourteen deaths in eleven months in a city of 8.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">million people – even when six of the deaths come close together</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> – is not carnage. We need to balance the concern and anger about cycling deaths, which we share, against the risk of exaggerating the dangers, scaring away potential cyclists, strengthening the hand of those who want to discourage cycling, and deterring f</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">uture politicians from becoming involved in the issue. In the debate at the moment, that balance is not being achieved. Significant collateral damage may be being caused to the very thing, cycling, that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">all sides in the debate</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> wish to promote. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">We fear that the all-consuming focus on cycling deaths may be deterring cyclists. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:10.78pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2012</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">/13</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> appears to be the year when the previously high growth in London’s cycling came almost to a halt. In the first four years of the Mayor’s term, growth in cycling on the TfL main roads averaged around </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">9</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> per cent a year (and more than 15 per cent in the year</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> 2010</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">/11</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.) The final figures for 2012</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">/13</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">show that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> growth last year appears to have been much lower, around 1 per cent. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:10.78pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">There are many explanations – the unusually wet spring and summer that year, the unusually cold winter, and the number of special even</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ts such as the Olympics and Jubilee which disrupted normal life. But 2012 was also the year when media and political coverage of cycling started to be dominated by the issue of deaths - even though, as we have already said, the number of deaths was actuall</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">y less than before. We believe that the all-consuming focus on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">supposed </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">cyclist “carnage” in 2012 may have helped deter people from cycling. It is too early to say whether the current furore will have the same effect, but we fear that it might. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">By the ve</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">ry act of trying to help cyclists, we are treated as if we have nationalised every accident.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:10.78pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Paradoxically, by planning to do</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> so much for cycling, the Mayor is attracting more criticism than if he had done nothing. City Hall is held responsible </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">by some </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">fo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">r every death and injury on the roads, however caused</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and whether or not the road concerned is even one of the 5% of roads for which the Mayor is responsible. That will not deter him – but the risk is that future politicians may conclude they should avoid</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> this subject. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Some of the assumptions in the debate are wrong.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:10.78pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">One school of thought appears to blame all cycling deaths on cyclists themselves. In other quarters, it is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">often</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> assumed that every death or accident is the fault of the motorist or the roa</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">d design. Any attempt to suggest that cyclists are also sometimes to blame is treated as impermissible. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:10.78pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">But of course there is a mix of causes in these events, and cyclists sometimes are to blame. We and the boroughs recognise our responsibility to provi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">de safer roads; but we make no apology whatever for also stressing cyclists’ responsibility to use the roads safely.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><br style="page-break-before:always; clear:both" /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Even the best infrastructure in the world cannot remove the responsibility to behave safely, or entirely immunise cyclists against harm</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:10.78pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal">Even with separated tracks on every street and an almost car-free city centre,  Europe’s most cycle-friendly city, Amsterdam, averages six deaths a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal">year</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal">, in a place with about the same number of bike trips as London (Amsterdamers cycle more often, but there are fewer of them). </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:10.78pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The chief executive of the London Cycling Campaign </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal">wrote two weeks ago: “We want to know when the dying will stop.” We can, and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal">we do, promise to improve provision and safety. But we cannot, and do not, promise to eliminate cyclist deaths. If that is the test the cycling lobby wishes to set us, we and every large city on earth will fail. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:10.78pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">urning every future cyclist death into a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">crisis risks actually slowing down, not speeding up, the rate of change. It diverts time and attention away from implementing the cycling programme and into crisis management; and it risks making decisionmakers more cautious. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">We do not say that people should stop talking about safety. It is the number one deterrent to taking up cycling. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:10.78pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">But we </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">do say</span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> they should be more careful in how they talk about it – and in particular, about the language they use, the assumptions they ma</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ke and the conclusions they draw from tragic, but exceptional, events. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">3. Lorries – and whether it is desirable or feasible to prohibit them from entering city centres at peak hours</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:10.78pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Between 2008 and 2012 HGVs were involved in 53 per cent of London’s cy</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">clist deaths, despite making up only 3 per cent of the traffic. HGVs have been involved in nine of the 14 deaths so far this year. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:10.78pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Our new segregated and semi-segregated </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">S</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">uperhighways, and c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ycle-separated</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> junctions, will better separate and protect cycli</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">sts from heavy lorries. Our new Quietway routes on low-traffic backstreets will enable cyclists to avoid lorries altogether. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:10.78pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">But we are also taking, or considering, a number of specific actions directly addressed at HGVs and their operators.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">The Mayor </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">is acting to remove the most unsafe lorries from London.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:10.78pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In September the Mayor announced he proposed to levy a “Safer Lorry Charge” on any vehicle which is not fitted with basic safety equipment to protect cyclists – such as </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">mirrors and sideguards. Many </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">classes of vehicle, mostly construction vehicles, are exempt from any legal requirement to fit it and are disproportionately involved in the HGV deaths. The</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> proposal</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> is to impose a daily charge at a rate high enough</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to render uneconomic the operation of an</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">y such vehicle in London. Consultation will start in January.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">We are stepping up enforcement against dangerous HGVs. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:10.78pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Cycling Vision expanded the Commercial Vehicle Unit, a specialist force of police officers. Part of their job is to investigate ser</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ious HGV-cyclist collisions, spotting patterns with particular operators or types of vehicle, and gathering the best possible evidence for prosecutions. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:10.78pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Another part of their job is to conduct on-street enforcement against unsafe lorries. Operations of t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">his nature have turne</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">d up high numbers of breaches of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the existing law. R</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ecent operation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s have found that two-thirds </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of all HGVs stopped in breach </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of existing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">regulations. These operations will be greatly expanded in future and can, we believe, have a sign</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ificant effect on safety. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:10.78pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">As mentioned, we are pressing the DfT for the removal of some other exemptions on safety requirements for lorries and pressing the EU to allow safer designs of lorry. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:10.78pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We are pressing for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">vulnerable road user awareness </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to be made part of the HGV driving test and the Certificate of Professional Competence. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">We have a wide variety of programmes to mandate higher standards for lorries and drivers; and to encourage lorries and cycles to be more aware of each other. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:10.78pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">TfL’s </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Freight Operator Recognition Scheme (FORS) has put thousands of lorry drivers on bicycles to experience the road from a cyclist’s point of view. Obtaining FORS accreditation requires significantly higher standards of safety and driver performance than the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">legal requirement. The Met’s Exchanging Places scheme puts cyclists in the cab of a lorry to understand drivers’ blind spots.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:10.78pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">All TfL subsidiaries (for example Crossrail) contractually require the highest possible standards of cycle safety equipment on th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">eir lorries. Because we are a big customer, this has a major effect on the market.  </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:10.78pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">As part of our trials at the Transport Research Laboratory, we are investigating the fitting of electronic sensor equipment to lorries to detect cyclists. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">We are lookin</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">g at different ways of shifting lorries outside of the peak</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:10.78pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">As stated in the Mayor’s Cycling Vision, we will study the experience from cities such as Paris and Dublin, where lorries over a certain size are restricted from certain parts of the city or at c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ertain times of the day. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:10.78pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We need to fully understand the range of impacts that a similar scheme would have in London, and are undertaking work to study this in detail. It is too early to pre-empt the outcome of this work, however on one hand, a peak hour</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> restriction could have significant road safety benefits and would reduce conflict between lorries travelling in the peak and cyclists commuting to work. On the other hand, a peak restriction may result in an increase in the number of smaller commercial ve</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">hicles during the rush hour.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:10.78pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Part of our study builds on the recommendations of the Mayor’s Roads Task Force and involves looking at other alternatives – including the experience of the Olympics, when we substantially reduced the number of peak-hour lorry</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> movements, and whether this is possible on a permanent basis, not just temporarily. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">November 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:8pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Foundry Form Sans'; font-size:8pt">There are two different ways of measuring cycle use. “Journeys” are where all or part of the journey was made by bike. “Trips” (about 181 million in London in 2011) are where the entire journey was made by bike. For instance, cycling to the station to get </span><span style="font-family:'Foundry Form Sans'; font-size:8pt">a train would count towards the first figure but not the second. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Georgia; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p></body></html>